\section{Data}
Data comes to us in the form of \textbf{observations} (measurements) which we symbolically write as
$$x_1,x_2, \ldots , x_n$$
where $x_i$ is an individual observation, and the index $i=1, \ldots , n$. %\pause

Here $n$ is referred to as \textbf{sample size}.% \pause

We can also write this as
$$x_i : \ \ i=1, \ldots , n$$%\pause
or in tabular form as
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|}\hline
observation&$x_1$&$x_2$&$\cdots$&$x_n$
 \\ \hline
index&1&2&$\cdots$&$n$ \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}


A small example is the following which could represent the weekly hours a student
studies in the first 5 weeks of STAT*2060.%\pause
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}\hline
observation&4&3&6&20&2
 \\ \hline
index&1&2&3&4&5 \\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
Here $n=5$  and $x_1=4, x_2=3, x_3=6,x_4=20, x_5=2$.
\section{Measures of Location}

\subsection{Mean}



The \textbf{mean} of data is obtained by adding up all of the observations and dividing by the
sample size (number of observations) and we symbolically use
$$\bar{x}$$ %\pause

\begin{itemize}
\item if $x_1,\ldots ,x_n$ is the data
\item then
$\bar{x} = \frac{x_1+x_2+\cdots +x_n}{n}$
\item for our example $\frac{4+3+6+20+2}{5}=\frac{35}{5}=7$
\item before going any further we need a more convenient way to write $x_1+x_2+\cdots +x_n$!
\end{itemize}



