\subsection{Variance and Standard Deviation}


The \textbf{variance}, or \textbf{sample variance} measures this spread %\pause

\bigskip

$$s^2 = \frac1{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(x_i -\bar{x}\right)^2$$



%\pause

But because of the squaring of units, we take the square root to
get the \textbf{(sample) standard deviation} %\pause

\bigskip

$$s = \sqrt{\frac1{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(x_i -\bar{x}\right)^2}$$



A small example is the following which could represent the weekly hours a student
studies in the first 5 weeks of STAT*2060.  Mean is 7.%\pause
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|c|c|c|}\hline
index&1&2&3&4&5 \\ \hline
observation&4&3&6&20&2\\ \hline
observation - mean&-3&-4&-1&13&-5\\ \hline
(observation - mean)$^2$&9&16&1&169&25\\ \hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}
$s^2 = 220/4=55$ hence $s=7.416$.


$$
s^2 = \frac1{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^n\left(x_i -\bar{x}\right)^2$$

or

$$
s^2 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^nx_i^2 -\frac{\left(\sum_{i=1}^nx_i\right)^2}{n}}
{n-1}
$$




\subsection{Percentiles Quartiles IQR and Boxplots}

The \textbf{$pth$ percentile} is a number  obtained from the observations such that $p\%$ of the measurements fall below that number.%\pause

\bigskip

The median is therefore the $50th$ percentile.  %\pause

\bigskip

The $25th$ percentile is called the \textbf{lower quartile $Q_L$} (lower hinge). %\pause

\bigskip

The $75th$ percentile is called the \textbf{upper quartile $Q_U$} (upper hinge).  %\pause

\bigskip

The \textbf{interquartile range ($IQR$)} is the distance between the lower and upper quartile
$$ IQR = Q_U-Q_L$$


Further definitions %\pause

\bigskip

\textbf{Lower inner fence} = Lower hinge -1.5($IQR$)%\pause

\bigskip

\textbf{Upper inner fence} = Upper hinge +1.5($IQR$)%\pause




One puts all of these ingredients together by doing the following:
\begin{itemize}
\item draw a horizontal line for the median
\item draw horizontal lines for the lower hinge and upper hinge
and inscribe a box
\item draw a vertical line from the lower hinge to the lower inner fence (called whiskers)
\item draw a vertical line from the upper hinge to the upper inner fence (called whiskers)
\item all other data points beyond the whiskers represent by * or $\circ$
\end{itemize}



We need to have a slightly larger data set in order to have meaningful interpretations.
Therefore suppose, we obtain a little more data.%\pause
