\section{Empirical rule}

\subsection{Relatioship between $\bar{x}$ and $s$}


There is a relationship between $\bar{x}$ and $s$.  %\pause

\bigskip

For any number $k > 1$, {\bf at least} $(1-1/k^2)$ of the measurements will fall
within $k$ standard deviations of the mean.  %\pause

\bigskip

Alternatively, if we look at the interval from $\bar{x} - k s$ to $\bar{x}+ks$ then
$(1-1/k^2) \%$ of the data will lie in that interval.

There is a relationship between $\bar{x}$ and $s$, and occurs usually
for large $n$  %\pause

\bigskip

The range from $\bar{x}-s$ to $\bar{x}+s$ is approximately 68\%. %\pause

\bigskip

The range from $\bar{x}-2s$ to $\bar{x}+2s$ is approximately 95\%. %\pause

\bigskip

The range from $\bar{x}-3s$ to $\bar{x}+3s$ is approximately 99\%. %\pause


For our study data we had $\bar{x}=8.56$ and $s=8.34$.

