\section{The Linear Equation}
\label{ssec.lineq}\markright{\ref{ssec.lineq}
\titleref{ssec.lineq}}

In this section, you will learn how to find a particular solution
and the general solution to any linear equation. A {\bf linear equation}\index{linear equation}
in $n$ variables $x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n$ is
one which can be expressed in the following form:
\begin{equation}
\label{leq1} a_1x_1 + a_2x_2 + \cdots + a_nx_n = b
\end{equation}
where $a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n$ are real fixed constants (or
scalars), called {\bf coefficients}, $b$ is a real constant, and
$x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n$ are the unknowns or variables.

Some examples of linear equations are: $$ 2x + y = 5, \ \ \ x_1 -
3x_2 +x_3 - x_4 = 8, \ \ \ \ y = \frac{3}{5}x + 5z -2, \ \ \ \ x_1
+ x_2 + \cdots + x_n = 2. $$ Anything not of this form is called
{\bf non-linear}. Equations containing roots, squares or products
of variables will be non-linear. Some examples of non-linear
equations are: $$ x^4 + 3y = 11, \ \ \ \ x + y - z + xy= 4, \ \ \
\ y - 2\sin(x) = 0, \ \ \ \ \sqrt{x_1} + x_2 + 5x_3 = 23. $$

A set of numbers $s_1, s_2, \ldots, s_n$ is a {\bf solution}\index{solution} to
the linear equation (\ref{leq1}) if it satisfies the equation
$$a_1s_1 + a_2s_2 + \cdots + a_ns_n = b. $$ A solution need not
be unique. We will call the set of all solutions the {\bf solution
set}\index{solution set} or the {\bf general solution}\index{general solution}. Any given numerical solution
in the set is called a {\bf particular solution}\index{particular solution}.

\begin{example}
\label{exam1.solution1}  Find the general solution to $6x - 3y =
1$.

To solve, assign an arbitrary value $t$ to $x$, and solve for $y$.
\begin{eqnarray*}
Let \  x = t & \Rightarrow &  6t - 3y = 1 \\
 & \Leftrightarrow & 6t - 1 = 3y \\
 & \Leftrightarrow & y = 2t - \frac{1}{3} \quad.
\end{eqnarray*}
Solution set : \{$(t, 2t - \frac{1}{3}) : t \in \mbox{\tebbb R}$ \}.
A numerical solution can be found by assigning a particular value
to $t$: if $t = 1$ then  $x = 1; \ y = 2 \cdot (1) - \frac{1}{3} =
\frac{5}{3}$.

Alternatively, assign an arbitrary value to $y$ and solve for $x$.
\begin{eqnarray*}
Let \  y = t & \Rightarrow  & 6x - 3t = 1 \\ & \Leftrightarrow &
6x = 1+ 3t \\
 & \Leftrightarrow & x = \frac{1}{6} +\frac{1}{2}t \quad .
\end{eqnarray*} Solution set : \{$( \frac{1}{6} + \frac{1}{2}t,t) :
t \in \mbox{\tebbb R}$ \}. This solution set is equivalent to the
one previously found.
\end{example}

\begin{example}
\label{exam1.solution2}  Find the general solution to $2x_1 - x_2
+ 3x_3 = 9$.

Assign arbitrary values, $s$ and $t$, to any two of the variables
and solve for the third variable.
\begin{eqnarray*}
Let \ x_1 = s, x_2=t & \Rightarrow & 2s - t + 3x_3 = 9 \\
  & \Leftrightarrow & 3x_3 = 9 - 2s + t \\
  & \Leftrightarrow & x_3 = 3 - \frac{2}{3}s +
  \frac{1}{3}t \quad.
\end{eqnarray*}
Solution set : \{$(s, t, 3 - \frac{2}{3}s + \frac{1}{3}t) : s, t
\in \mbox{\tebbb R}$ \}.
\end{example}

