system of equations:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Give the corresponding augmented matrix, and
\item Write the system as $A{\bf x}={\bf b}$. Which one is the
coefficient matrix?
\end{enumerate}
\noindent The answers can be found in section \ref {ssec.answers1}.
\begin{eqnarray*}
x_1-2x_2+x_3+2x_4&=&5\\
3&=&x_1+x_3-2\\
x_2+1&=&x_3+2x_4
\end{eqnarray*}
\section{Row Reduction}\index{row reduction}
\label{ssec.rreduction}   \markright{\ref{ssec.rreduction}
\titleref{ssec.rreduction}}
 When dealing with systems of equations, we
are interested in finding the solution set.  Any equation in a
linear system can be multiplied by a nonzero\index{nonzero} term without changing
the system itself. Since each row of the augmented matrix
represents an equation, we can also multiply rows by nonzero
terms. Similarly, interchanging rows in the augmented matrix does
not change the system or the solution; it is the same as changing
the orders of equations in a system. Adding multiples of one row
to another row does not change the solution set. These three
operations are called elementary row operations and will be used
to help find the solution set.

To summarize, an {\bf elementary row operation}\index{elementary row operation} is any one of the
following:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Multiply equation/row by a nonzero constant.
\item Interchange two equations/rows.
\item Add multiples of one equation/row to another.
\end{enumerate}

\noindent {\bf Activity \ref{ssec.rreduction}}

\noindent For the following three sets of matrices, determine which
row operation was performed on the first matrix to take it to the
second matrix. Then, write each augmented matrix as a linear
system, and verify that the row operations performed on the matrix
are the same as the operations performed on each equation.
\begin{enumerate}
\item $\left [ \begin{array}{rrrcr} 1&1&3&\vline&-2\\ 0&2&-1&\vline&4
\end{array} \right ] \leadsto \left [ \begin{array}{rrrcr} 1&1&3& \vline
&-2\\ 0&1&-\frac{1}{2}&\vline&2 \end{array} \right ]$
\item $\left [ \begin{array}{rrrcr}1&0.1&3&\vline&-2\\2&0&-1&\vline&4 \\
6&-1&-2&\vline&1\end{array} \right ] \leadsto \left [
\begin{array}{rrrcr} 1&0.1&3&\vline&-2\\6&-1&-2&\vline&1 \\
2&0&-1&\vline &4\end{array} \right ]$
\item $\left [ \begin{array}{rrcr} 1&-1&\vline&2\\2&1&\vline&1 \end{array} \right ]
\leadsto \left [ \begin{array}{rrcr} 1&-1&\vline&2\\0&3&\vline&-3
\end{array} \right ]$.
\end{enumerate}
\noindent The answers can be found in section \ref{ssec.answers1}.

The objective of row reduction is to replace the given system with
a new system which has the same solution set, but which is easier
to solve.  The following example demonstrates the use of the three
elementary row operations in finding the solution to a linear
system written in augmented matrix form. The corresponding system
is also given to demonstrate the equivalence of the matrix operations
and the operations on the corresponding equations.

