\section{The Number of Solutions to a System of Equations}
\label{ssec.nofsolutions}\markright{\ref{ssec.nofsolutions}
\titleref{ssec.nofsolutions}}
There are three types of solutions to systems of linear
equations.  These types are
\begin{enumerate}
\item No solution,
\item An infinite number of solutions,
\item A unique solution.
\end{enumerate}

The three types have been displayed in Example \ref{exam1.reduce}.  At
this point it is beneficial to re-examine the example to see
how the form of the row-echelon matrix determines the type of
solution.

First note that in Example \ref{exam1.reduce}(c) the row-echelon matrix
had a row \\$\left [ \begin{array}{rrrcr}
0 & 0 & 0 & \vline & 1 \end{array} \right]$
and from
this we deduced that there
was no solution.  This consideration would apply to the row-echelon
matrix for any system: if there is a row
$\left[ \begin{array}
  {rrrcr}  0 & \cdots & 0  & \vline & \alpha   \end{array}\right]$
  $(\alpha \neq 0)$
  then  this  means $$0x_1  + 0x_2 + \cdots +  0x_n = \alpha\ {\rm with}\
  (\alpha \neq 0),$$
  and  there   can  be  no   solution.

  If the above does not occur then the type of solution
  will depend on whether there are non-leading variables.  If there
  is a non-leading variable (e.g. as in Example \ref {exam1.reduce}(b)) we solve
  for the leading variables in terms of the non-leading variable.  There
  is a different solution for each value of the non-leading variable
  and thus an infinite number of solutions.  If there are no
  non-leading variables (i.e. all variables are leading as in Example
  \ref{exam1.reduce}(a)) then there is a unique solution.  To summarize,
\begin{enumerate}
\item If there exists a row $0~0 ...0|\alpha~(\alpha \neq 0)$ in the
row-echelon (or reduced row-echelon) form, then the system is
inconsistent and there is no solution (see Example
\ref{exam1.reduce}(c)).
\item If 1) does not apply, and if there exists a non-leading (or free)
variable, then there is an infinite number of solutions (see
Example \ref{exam1.reduce}(b)).
\item If 1) does not apply, and if every variable is leading, then there
is a unique solution (see Example \ref{exam1.reduce}(a)). In this
case the reduced row-echelon form is
$$\left[ \begin{array}{rrrrcr} 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & \vline & \alpha_{1} \\
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0 & \vline & \alpha_{2} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots
&\vline& \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 & \vline & \alpha_{n}
\\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & \vline &0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots &\vline&
\vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & \vline &0
\end{array} \right].$$
\end{enumerate}
\noindent
and the solution is $x_{1}=\alpha_{1}, x_{2}=\alpha_{2}, ..., x_{n}=\alpha_{n}$.

To determine which of the three types of solution applies, simply
follow the chart:

\begin{center}
\begin{picture}(50,50)(-50,-50)
\put(-150,-10){Is~there~a~row} \put(-155,-20){$0~0
...0|\alpha~(\alpha \neq 0)?$} \put(5,-125){Unique~Solution}
\put(-155,-70){Inconsistent~System,} \put (-145,-80){No~Solution}
\put(0,-70){Is~there~a~free} \put(15,-80){variable ?}
\put(-130,-125){Infinite~Number~of} \put(-110,-135){Solutions}
\put(-135,-40){Yes} \put(-40,-40){No} \put(-35,-100){Yes}
\put(40,-100){No} \put(-110,-25){\vector(0,-1){30}}
