\subsection*{Homogeneous systems}\index{homogeneous systems}

Row reduction can also be used to solve homogeneous systems. For
example, consider the following homogeneous system

$$ \left[ \begin{array}{rrrrrcr} 3 & 3 & -1 & 0 & 2 & \vline & 0
\\ 1 & 1 & -1 & 0 & 0 & \vline & 0 \\ 2 & 2 & -2 & 0 & 0 & \vline &0
\\ 0 & 1 & 1 & 0 & 1 & \vline &0
\end{array}
 \right] \stackrel{row \ reduction}{\leadsto}
   \left[
\begin{array}{rrrrrcr} 1 & 0 & 0 & 0 & 1 & \vline &0 \\ 0 & 1 & 0
& 0 & 0 & \vline &0 \\ 0 & 0 & 1 & 0 & 1 & \vline &0 \\ 0 & 0 & 0
& 0 & 0 & \vline & 0
\end{array}
 \right].
$$ The corresponding system of equations is: $$
\begin{array}{ccccccc}
 x_1 & & & &+ x_5 &= & 0 \\
 & x_2&  & & & = & 0 \\
 & & x_3& & +x_5&= & 0 \end{array} \Rightarrow \begin{array}{ccc}
                                            x_1 &= & - x_5 \\
                                            x_2&=&0\\
                                            x_3&= &- x_5
                                            \end{array}.
$$ Let $ x_4 = s \mbox{ and } x_5 =t $, then
        $$
        \begin{array}{ccr}
         x_1 &=& -t \\
         x_2&=&0 \\
         x_3 &=& -t \\ x_4&=&s \\x_5&=&t  \end{array} .
        $$
There are an infinite number of solutions because there is a free variable.
For a homogenous system it is not possible to obtain a row  $0~0 ...0|\alpha~(\alpha
\neq 0)$.This means that a homogenous system will never be inconsistent (the trivial
solution $x_{1}=x_{2}=...=x_{n}=0$ always exists). Consequently there are only two
possible forms of solution:
\begin{enumerate}
\item The system has only the trivial solution (all variables are leading).
\item The system has infinitely many solutions (there exists a free variable).
\end{enumerate}
A homogeneous system of linear equations with more unknowns than
equations has infinitely many solutions. Elementary row operations
cannot alter the last column of zeroes in the augmented matrix of
a homogeneous system. Therefore, the reduced row-echelon form is
also homogeneous.

\section{Reduced Row Echelon versus Row Echelon Form}
\label{ssec.rrevref}\markright{\ref{ssec.rrevref}
\titleref{ssec.rrevref}}

Although it is a matter of choice whether you use the
row-echelon or the reduced row-echelon form, you should be
aware of the following points.
\begin{enumerate}
\item Less work is required to achieve the row-echelon form then
is required to achieve the reduced row-echelon form.  The {\bf
type} of solution depends on whether there is a row
{$0~0...0|\alpha~(\alpha \neq 0)$} and whether there is a free
variable. Both of these can be determined from the row-echelon
form. Therefore, if you are interested in the {\bf type} of
solution only, the row-echelon form would be the more sensible
choice. \item For an nxn matrix A, if you count the number of
arithmetic calculations required to
\begin{enumerate}
\item  put A in reduced row-echelon form and read off the solution,or
\item  put A in row-echelon form and solve by back substitution,
\end{enumerate}
then it turns out that less calculations are required for (b) than
for (a).  The difference is negligable for small values of n and
it doesn't matter which way you do it for the size of matrix
encountered in this course.  However for large values of n, when
the calculation is done by computer, row-echelon form with back
substitution is preferred. \item While 1 and 2 above point to use
of the row-echelon form, the reduced row-echelon form can have
advantages.  For example, if the reduced row-echelon form is
\end{enumerate}
$$\left[ \begin{array}{rrrrcr} 1 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & \vline & \alpha_{1} \\
0 & 1 & \cdots & 0 & \vline & \alpha_{2} \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots
&\vline& \vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 1 & \vline & \alpha_{n}
\\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & \vline &0 \\ \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots &\vline&
\vdots \\ 0 & 0 & \cdots & 0 & \vline &0
\end{array} \right]  . $$
then the extreme right hand column gives the solution:
$x_1=\alpha_1, x_2=\alpha_2,\cdots,x_n=\alpha_n.$  This fact will be used in
section \ref{ssec.findinv}.

\section{Summary}\label{ssec.sumry2}
\markright{\ref{ssec.sumry2} \titleref{ssec.sumry2}}
{\bf Section Keywords: Augmented matrix; back
substitution; coefficient; consistent; elementary row operations;
Gauss-Jordan elimination; general solution; homogeneous;
inconsistent; linear equation; linear system; non-homogeneous;
particular solution; reduced row-echelon form; row-echelon form;
solution set; trivial solution.}
\\ \\
In this section, we have had to find the solution to systems of
linear equations.  These systems are either homogeneous or
non-homogeneous.  They may have no solution (inconsistent), one
solution or an infinite number of solutions (consistent).  We have
found the solution to these systems by forming the augmented
matrix of the coefficients and the constants.  Using elementary
row operations, the augmented matrix has been reduced to reduced
row-echelon form (Gauss-Jordan elimination).  From there, the
solution is easily found by writing the augmented matrix in its
corresponding equation form. Reducing to row-echelon form and
using back substitution is a second method to find the solution.


Using Gaussian elimination to solve systems of equations can be
frustrating in the beginning.  Make sure to label the row
operations performed. If any mistakes are made, this practice will
make the search for the mistake much easier. Fractions are an
inevitability, so  pay attention to the arithmetic. A simple
mistake adding or subtracting in the beginning could dramatically
change the answer found. Don't give up after the first attempt!

